{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b7a15aa-5a1a-4014-a087-bbf50425e6a8","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `.vscode/mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Place this file at **`.vscode/mcp.json`** in your workspace root.\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your C# server must read MCP JSON-RPC messages from stdin and write responses to stdout (don't use `Console.WriteLine` for logging — use stderr instead).\n- If you publish the server as a tool, replace `dotnet run --project ...` with the path to the built executable.\n\nIf your server uses **SSE/HTTP** transport instead, use:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"sse\",\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:5000/sse\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"542307ea-4b3e-428e-ace2-c2bd57fc68c5","outputTokens":310,"requestId":"1584:301230:315EC8D:360E03F:69FBE59D"},"id":"3623e673-a650-401f-93c6-bd7da3503bff","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:06:45.043Z","parentId":"4e2c4a0c-2c3d-40e7-b668-de2b9e64f281"}
